Tiktik: Strategic Product Plan & Competitive Analysis
Executive Summary
Tiktik has a strong foundation as a vanilla JavaScript notification library with premium GSAP-powered "Dynamic Island" aesthetics. However, to surpass industry leaders like Sonner, React-Hot-Toast, and React-Toastify, Tiktik must evolve. This document outlines a strategic roadmap to elevate Tiktik from a specialized animation library to the definitive, high-performance, accessible notification standard for the modern web.

1. Competitive Analysis
React-Toastify
Position: The Legacy Standard

Strengths: Incredibly feature-rich (swipe-to-close, pause on focus loss), widely adopted, extensive customization API.
Weaknesses: Large bundle size (~16KB gzipped), visually dated default design, React-only.
Tiktik's Advantage: Tiktik is framework-agnostic (Vanilla JS) and offers vastly superior out-of-the-box motion design.
React Hot Toast
Position: The Minimalist Favorite

Strengths: Extremely lightweight (<5KB gzipped), elegant default styles, headless useToaster mode for custom rendering.
Weaknesses: Fewer built-in features, basic animations, React-only.
Tiktik's Advantage: Tiktik offers "wow-factor" GSAP animations and complex content handling (progress bars, expanded content) that Hot Toast lacks.
Sonner
Position: The Modern Developer's Choice (Next.js / shadcn/ui)

Strengths: Exceptional developer experience (DX), highly accessible, buttery smooth layout projections, simple API, natively handles complex stacking.
Weaknesses: Highly opinionated API, React-specific (though ported to others).
Tiktik's Advantage: Tiktik brings Sonner-level aesthetics to the entire web ecosystem, not just React, and utilizes GSAP for more complex physics-based motion.
Notyf / Toastify.js (Vanilla JS Competitors)
Position: The Vanilla Alternatives

Strengths: Zero dependencies, very small footprint, easy to drop into plain HTML.
Weaknesses: Basic CSS transitions, limited complex interactivity, poor accessibility out-of-the-box.
Tiktik's Advantage: Tiktik bridges the gap between the simplicity of vanilla JS and the premium feel of modern React libraries.
