3. Identified Weaknesses in Tiktik
Despite its premium feel, Tiktik falls short in several key areas necessary for market dominance:

Accessibility (WCAG Compliance):

Lacks prefers-reduced-motion media queries to automatically disable GSAP physics for users with vestibular disorders.
Screen reader announcements exist (role="alert"), but lack nuanced focus management when action buttons are present.
No built-in keyboard shortcut to jump focus to the active toast container.
Advanced Interaction Patterns:

No Swipe-to-Dismiss: A critical expectation for modern mobile UX.
Stacking Physics: Current GSAP reflow is basic. It lacks the overlapping, card-deck style "peeking" stack popularized by Sonner.
Developer Experience (DX) & Ecosystem:

No Native Framework Wrappers: While vanilla JS is great, developers want idiomatic wrappers (<TiktikProvider />, useToast()) for React, Vue, and Svelte.
Bundle Size: Relying on GSAP as a peer dependency limits adoption for highly size-constrained projects.
Extensibility:

No rendering hooks or "Headless Mode". Users cannot entirely replace the DOM structure of the toast while keeping the logic/animations.
4. Strategic Improvement Roadmap
Phase 1: The UX & Accessibility Overhaul (Immediate Priority)
Implement Swipe-to-Dismiss: Add touch/mouse drag physics handling (interpolated by GSAP when available) to swipe toasts away.
WCAG Strict Compliance:
Add prefers-reduced-motion detection mapped to Tiktik's animationSpeed = 0 or CSS fallback toggle.
Implement a keyboard shortcut (e.g., Alt + T, customizable) to move focus directly to the toast region.
Modern "Deck" Stacking: Overhaul the stacking algorithm to emulate Sonner's overlapping deck style, saving screen space when multiple toasts appear.
Phase 2: The DX & Framework Expansion (Mid-term)
First-Party React/Vue/Svelte Wrappers: Create official packages (@tiktik/react, @tiktik/vue) that wrap the vanilla core, providing hooks like useTiktik() and components.
Headless Mode / Custom Renderers: Allow developers to pass a custom DOM element or framework component into 
showToast
, bypassing the default pill UI entirely.
Phase 3: Performance & Optimization (Long-term)
GSAP Decoupling / WAAPI Migration: Investigate moving the exact GSAP elastic easing curves to the native Web Animations API (WAAPI) to remove the GSAP peer dependency entirely while maintaining the exact same physics.
Lazy Loading: Implement code-splitting for complex features (like progress bars or promise handling) so the base bundle drops below 5KB.
5. Positioning Statement
"Tiktik is the definitive notification engine for the modern web. It combines the premium, physics-based 'Dynamic Island' fluid motion expected in top-tier apps with the universal compatibility of Vanilla JavaScript. Unchained from specific frameworks, Tiktik delivers Sonner-level aesthetics, enterprise-grade accessibility, and unmatched interactive flexibility to any stack."

